text:
The village post Office, located at the S.E. corner of Old Broadway (right) and West 129th Street (left). This office was discontinued in July 1863 and George W. Bromleys Atlas of 1879 shows a similar office on the east side of this thoroughfare, midway between West 129th and 130th Streets. A. James Doyle was Postmaster of the office shown, from October 6, 1851 to April 9, 1861.

Unknown date.

April 1, 1938
F. L. Sperr

3221 Broadway, at the N.W. corner St. Clair Place (W. 129th Street), as photographed from under the elevated roadbed of the West Side Subway. To the right is a gas station occupying a former coal yard site. The Sinclair and Valentine Printing Ink Co. occupy a building that extends thru the block from St. Clair Place to W. 130th Street. The milk plant that is partially shown is at the S.W. corner of Broadway and 130th Street.

April 1, 1938

P.L. Sperr

Old Broadway (formerly Bloomingdale Road), north from W. 126th (formerly Lawrence) Street, showing this old thoroughfare curving westward in its northward trek. To the right (in view No. 1) is a three story unit of the Sheltering Arms and occupies the S.E. corner of W. 129th Street. View No. 2 shows only the buildings at the N.E. corner. They are numbered 29-31-33 Old Broadway; The latter two are of frame construction.

April 1, 1938.
Views 1 and 2

Manhattanville: A view of the west side of the Public Drive (Broadway) at West 127th Street (Tiemann Place) and showing the Thomas M. Finley Boarding School at the N.W. corner of same. This institution was in operation in 1811. In this structure were held the earlier services of St. Mary's P.E. Church, prior to the construction of the building on Lawrence Street in 1823. Today (1937) the Whitestone, an apartment house bearing No. 41-45 Tiemann Place, stands upon this site.
Unknown date.
